      "Amy Edmondson's research on psychological safety — one of the most cited bodies of work in contemporary organizational science — is often reduced to a simple proposition: teams that feel safe perform better. This reduction loses the most important part of the finding: psychological safety is a team-level perception that is created and destroyed by specific, observable leader behaviors. It's not a feeling that exists independently of those behaviors.",
