      "When an acquiring health system imposes its leadership and governance model on an acquired community hospital, it typically loses exactly the leaders who carry this institutional knowledge — because those leaders have made their careers in the acquired organization's culture, not the acquirer's, and because they correctly anticipate that they will have less authority and less organizational relevance in the integrated entity.",
      "The leadership integration planning that would prevent this outcome requires three things: genuine investment in understanding the acquired organization's informal leadership structure before closing; a transition design that builds trust with the key leaders in the acquired organization rather than simply assigning them to their new positions; and an explicit plan for how the two leadership cultures will converge rather than an implicit assumption that the acquired organization will simply adopt the acquirer's ways.",
      "Health systems that have learned from failed integrations consistently cite the same lesson: the financial model of the deal is planned with precision. The leadership model of the integration is planned with aspiration. Closing the gap between those two levels of rigor is the single highest-leverage intervention available in healthcare M&A.",
